{{About|the German-American actress|the British swimmer|Irene Gilbert (swimmer)|the Irish fashion designer|Irene Gilbert (fashion designer)}}
'''Irene Gilbert''' (born '''Irene Liebert or Liebeschutz'''; August 25, 1934 – May 21, 2011) was a [[Germany|German]]-born [[United States|American]] actress and acting school director, who co-founded the [[Stella Adler Studio of Acting#The Stella Adler Academy of Acting and Theatre, Los Angeles|Stella Adler Academy]] in [[Los Angeles]], with actress [[Joanne Linville]], in 1985.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|first=Valerie J.|last=Nelson|title=Irene Gilbert dies at 76; cofounder of Stella Adler's Los Angeles acting academy|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/may/28/local/la-me-irene-gilbert-20110528|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=2011-05-28|accessdate=2011-06-03}}</ref> She served as the academy's director for around two decades after the its establishment.<ref name=latimes/><ref name=variety>{{cite news|title=Actress Irene Gilbert ran LA acting academy|url=https://variety.com/2011/scene/people-news/irene-gilbert-dies-at-76-1118037742|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 31, 2011|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref>
==Early life== Gilbert was born as Irene Liebert or Liebeschutz in [[Brandenburg|Brandenburg, Germany]] on August 25, 1934.<ref name=latimes/> She immigrated to [[New York City]] with her parents, Gaston and Lucie Liebert (or Liebeschutz), just before the outbreak of [[World War II]]. Her parents were killed by a [[drunk driver]] when she was just five years old. She was raised by her aunt and her four older brothers.<ref name=latimes/>
==Career== She changed her surname to Gilbert when she began her acting career, reportedly because she felt that it eemed "movie-star-esque."<ref name=latimes/> Her acting career extended into the late 1980s. Her [[television]] credits included roles in ''[[Cannon (TV series)|Cannon]]'', ''[[Barnaby Jones]]'', and ''[[Emergency!]]'' in the 1970s.<ref name=latimes/>
Gilbert became friends with New York City-based acting coach [[Stella Adler]] during the 1960s.<ref name=latimes/> In 1985, Gilbert and actress [[Joanne Linville]] pursued Adler to open a branch of the [[Stella Adler Studio of Acting#The Stella Adler Academy of Acting and Theatre, Los Angeles|Stella Adler Academy]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=latimes/>
Gilbert also served as the school's director for 20 years.<ref name=latimes/> A fire at the school, which was originally located in a small theater at [[Hollywood Boulevard]] and Argyle Avenue, forced the school's temporary closure in 1991. The school's building was further threatened with [[demolition]] to make way for a [[Metro Rail (Los Angeles County)|proposed subway line]] at the time of Adler's death, in 1992.<ref name=latimes/>
Gilbert moved and reopened the school in 1994 at a building which was once the Embassy Club, a [[private club]] in the 1930s at Hollywood Boulevard and [[Highland Avenue (Los Angeles)|Highland Avenue]].<ref name=latimes/> She continued to teach acting at the school and produce stage productions. The Stella Adler Academy in Los Angeles named one of its theaters, the Irene Gilbert Theatre, in honor of her.<ref name=latimes/>
==Death== Married once, to Ronald Packenham Law, Irene Gilbert died, aged 76, from complications of [[Alzheimer's disease]], at the home of her son, Randall Garrett Herzon, in [[Eureka, California]].<ref name=variety/>
