'''Open learning''' is an innovative movement in education that emerged in the 1970s and evolved into fields of practice and study. The term refers generally to activities that either enhance learning opportunities within formal education systems or broaden learning opportunities beyond formal education systems.<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/02680510802625443#.UkCUrGRAQpt | title=Open Educational Resources: reviewing initiatives and issues | author=D'Antoni, Susan | journal=Open Learning | year=2009 | volume=24 | issue=1 (Special Issue) | pages=4 | doi=10.1080/02680510802625443}}</ref> Open learning involves but is not limited to: classroom teaching methods, approaches to interactive learning,<ref name=Mason1991>{{cite journal|last=Mason|first=Robin|title=Conference Report. Open learning in the 1990s, 12-14 September 1990, University of Lancaster, UK|journal=Open Learning|date=February 1991|volume=6|issue=1|pages=49–50|doi=10.1080/0268051910060109|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/0268051910060109#.UjyNRmRAQps|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref> formats in work-related education and training,<ref name=Bowen1987>{{cite journal|last=Bowen|first=Peter|title=Open learning formats in high performance training|journal=Open Learning|year=1987|volume=2|issue=2|pages=29–31|doi=10.1080/0268051870020206|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/0268051870020206?prevSearch=%2522open%2Blearning%2Bfor%2Bdevelopment%2522&searchHistoryKey=#.Ujym3WRAQps|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=Wilson2003>{{cite journal|last=Wilson|first=Valerie|author2=Ursula Schlapp |author3=Julia Davidson |title=Prescription for learning? Meeting the development needs of the pharmacy profession|journal=International Journal of Lifelong Education|year=2003|volume=22|issue=4|pages=380–95|doi=10.1080/02601370304833|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02601370304833#.UjywQmRAQps|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref> the cultures and ecologies of learning communities,<ref name=Chang2010>{{cite journal|last=Chang|first=Bo|title=Culture as a tool: facilitating knowledge construction in the context of a learning community|journal=International Journal of Lifelong Education|year=2010|volume=29|issue=6|pages=705–22|doi=10.1080/02601370.2010.523947|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/02601370.2010.523947#preview|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=Ehlers2013>{{cite book|last=Ehlers|first=Ulf-Daniel|title=Open Learning Cultures: A Guide to Quality, Evaluation, and Assessment for Future Learning|year=2013|publisher=Springer Verlag|location=Heidelberg|isbn=978-3-642-38173-7|pages=vii-viii, 43|url=https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-642-38174-4/page/1|accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref> and the development and use of [[open educational resources]]. While there is no agreed-upon, comprehensive definition of open learning, central focus is commonly placed on the "needs of the learner as perceived by the learner."<ref name=Coffey1988>{{cite journal|last=Coffey|first=John|title=Guest Editorial: The Opening Learning Movement|journal=Innovations in Education & Training International|year=1988|volume=25|issue=3|pages=195–96|doi=10.1080/1355800880250301|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/1355800880250301#.UjyV7WRAQps}}</ref> Case studies<ref name=Coffey1988 /><ref name=Dodds2001>{{cite journal|last=Dodds|first=Tony|title=Creating open and lifelong learning institutions in higher education: a Namibian case-study|journal=International Journal of Lifelong Education|year=2001|volume=20|issue=6|pages=502–10|doi=10.1080/02601370110088472|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02601370110088472#.UjywZ2RAQps|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref> illustrate open learning as an innovation both within and across academic disciplines, professions, social sectors and national boundaries, and in business and industry, higher education institutions, collaborative initiatives between institutions, and schooling for young learners.
==Inception==
Open learning as a [[teaching method]] is founded on the work of [[Célestin Freinet]] in France and [[Maria Montessori]] in Italy, among others. Open learning is supposed to allow pupils self-determined, independent and interest-guided learning. A prominent example is the language experience approach to teaching initial literacy (cf. [[Brügelmann]]/ [[Brinkmann]] 2011). More recent work on open learning has been conducted by the German pedagogues [[Hans Brügelmann]] (1975; 1999), [[Falko Peschel]] (2002), [[Jörg Ramseger]] (1977) and [[Wulf Wallrabenstein]] (1991). The approach is supposed to face up to three challenges (cf. in more detail Brügelmann/ Brinkmann 2008, chap. 1): * the vast differences in experiences, interests, and comptencies between children of the same age; * the constructivist nature of learning demanding active problem-solving by the learner him- and herself; * the legal requirement of student participation in decisions stipulated by the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child (CRC). of 1989.
